description:
Parse Claude Code's native MCP format from ~/.claude.json and .mcp.json into normalized McpServer types.

## Input Format (Claude Code)
```json
{
  "mcpServers": {
    "server-name": {
      "command": "npx",
      "args": ["-y", "@modelcontextprotocol/server-filesystem"],
      "env": { "KEY": "value" }
    }
  }
}
```

## Output
Vec<McpServer> with normalized types

## Files
- src/harness/claude_code.rs

## Acceptance Criteria
- [ ] Parse stdio servers (command + args)
- [ ] Parse SSE servers (type: sse)
- [ ] Parse HTTP servers (type: http)
- [ ] Handle env variable syntax (${VAR})
- [ ] Unit tests for each server type

Define the McpCapabilities struct that describes what MCP features each harness supports.

## McpCapabilities Struct

```rust
#[derive(Debug, Clone, PartialEq, Eq)]
pub struct McpCapabilities {
    /// Supports local stdio servers
    pub stdio: bool,

    /// Supports SSE remote servers
    pub sse: bool,

    /// Supports HTTP/Streamable HTTP remote servers
    pub http: bool,

    /// Supports OAuth for remote servers
    pub oauth: bool,

    /// Supports per-server timeout configuration
    pub timeout: bool,

    /// Supports enable/disable toggle
    pub toggle: bool,

    /// Supports custom headers for remote servers
    pub headers: bool,

    /// Supports working directory (cwd) for stdio
    pub cwd: bool,
}
```

## Implementation per Harness

```rust
impl Harness {
    pub fn mcp_capabilities(&self) -> McpCapabilities {
        match self.kind {
            HarnessKind::ClaudeCode => McpCapabilities {
                stdio: true,
                sse: true,
                http: true,
                oauth: false,
                timeout: false,
                toggle: false,
                headers: true,
                cwd: false,
            },
            HarnessKind::OpenCode => McpCapabilities {
                stdio: true,
                sse: false,  // Uses 'remote' type
                http: true,
                oauth: true,
                timeout: true,
                toggle: true,
                headers: true,
                cwd: false,
            },
            HarnessKind::Goose => McpCapabilities {
                stdio: true,
                sse: true,
                http: true,  // streamable_http
                oauth: false,
                timeout: true,  // In seconds, not ms
                toggle: true,
                headers: true,  // Only for streamable_http
                cwd: false,
            },
        }
    }

    /// Check if a specific server type is supported
    pub fn supports_mcp_server(&self, server: &McpServer) -> bool {
        let caps = self.mcp_capabilities();
        match server {
            McpServer::Stdio(_) => caps.stdio,
            McpServer::Sse(_) => caps.sse,
            McpServer::Http(_) => caps.http,
        }
    }
}
```

## Acceptance Criteria
- [ ] Capabilities accurately reflect each harness's features
- [ ] supports_mcp_server() helper works correctly
- [ ] Doc comments explain each capability

Define the EnvValue type that handles environment variable references with harness-specific syntax.

## Problem
Different harnesses use different syntax for env var references:
- Claude Code: \${VAR}
- OpenCode: {env:VAR}
- Goose: Uses env_keys array, plain values

## EnvValue Type

```rust
#[derive(Debug, Clone, Serialize, Deserialize, PartialEq, Eq)]
#[serde(untagged)]
pub enum EnvValue {
    /// Plain string value
    Plain(String),
    /// Reference to environment variable
    EnvRef { env: String },
}

impl EnvValue {
    /// Create a plain string value
    pub fn plain(s: impl Into<String>) -> Self {
        Self::Plain(s.into())
    }

    /// Create an environment variable reference
    pub fn env(var: impl Into<String>) -> Self {
        Self::EnvRef { env: var.into() }
    }

    /// Convert to harness-specific string format
    pub fn to_native(&self, kind: HarnessKind) -> String {
        match (self, kind) {
            (Self::Plain(s), _) => s.clone(),
            (Self::EnvRef { env }, HarnessKind::ClaudeCode) => format!("\${{{}}}}", env),
            (Self::EnvRef { env }, HarnessKind::OpenCode) => format!("{{env:{}}}", env),
            (Self::EnvRef { env }, HarnessKind::Goose) => {
                // Goose resolves at runtime, return empty or resolved
                std::env::var(env).unwrap_or_default()
            }
        }
    }

    /// Parse from harness-specific string format
    pub fn from_native(s: &str, kind: HarnessKind) -> Self {
        // Parse \${VAR} or {env:VAR} patterns
        // Return Plain if no pattern matched
    }

    /// Resolve the value, looking up env vars if needed
    pub fn resolve(&self) -> Option<String> {
        match self {
            Self::Plain(s) => Some(s.clone()),
            Self::EnvRef { env } => std::env::var(env).ok(),
        }
    }
}
```

## Usage Example

```rust
let api_key = EnvValue::env("MY_API_KEY");
let native = api_key.to_native(HarnessKind::ClaudeCode);
// Returns: "\${MY_API_KEY}"

let native = api_key.to_native(HarnessKind::OpenCode);
// Returns: "{env:MY_API_KEY}"
```

## Acceptance Criteria
- [ ] Supports plain strings and env references
- [ ] Converts to all three harness formats
- [ ] Parses from all three harness formats
- [ ] Serde untagged works correctly
- [ ] Unit tests for all conversions

Implement the mcp_to_native() converter for Claude Code harness.

## IMPORTANT: Use McpCapabilities Validation

Before converting, validate with `supports_mcp_server()`:

```rust
pub fn mcp_to_native(harness: &Harness, name: &str, server: &McpServer) -> Result<serde_json::Value> {
    if !harness.supports_mcp_server(server) {
        return Err(Error::UnsupportedMcpConfig {
            harness: harness.kind().to_string(),
            reason: "Server uses unsupported features".into(),
        });
    }
    // ... conversion logic
}
```

This catches cases like:
- HTTP server with OAuth (Claude doesn't support OAuth)
- Server with timeout_ms (Claude doesn't support timeout)

## Claude Code MCP Format

### Stdio Server
```json
{
  "server-name": {
    "command": "node",
    "args": ["/path/to/server.js"],
    "env": {
      "API_KEY": "${MY_API_KEY}"
    }
  }
}
```

### SSE Server
```json
{
  "server-name": {
    "type": "sse",
    "url": "https://example.com/sse"
  }
}
```

### HTTP Server
```json
{
  "server-name": {
    "type": "http",
    "url": "https://api.example.com/mcp",
    "headers": {
      "Authorization": "Bearer ${TOKEN}"
    }
  }
}
```

## Key Differences
- Stdio is default (no type field needed)
- Uses ${VAR} for env var substitution
- No enabled/disabled toggle
- No timeout field
- env not environment

## Acceptance Criteria
- [ ] Validates with supports_mcp_server() before converting
- [ ] Returns Result<Value, Error> not just Value
- [ ] Correctly converts all three transport types
- [ ] Uses ${VAR} syntax for env values
- [ ] Omits optional fields when empty
- [ ] Unit tests cover validation failures

